	<section id="presentation_audio" expanded="true">
		<audio id="narration01">
			<file play="true" startpos="1" bytes="26371" duration="78">a_02_03_01_010_01.swf</file>
			<transcript translate="true">Just as infants are born wired to seek interaction and connection, parents are wired to respond.</transcript>
			<notes id="mentor-character">Narrator:</notes>
		</audio>
		<audio id="narration02">
			<file play="false" startpos="1" bytes="164627" duration="480">a_02_03_01_010_02.swf</file>
			<transcript translate="true">Some recent research has focused on mirror neurons, a biological mechanism that enables parents to respond to their infants. Mirror neurons are a class of neurons that are activated by the brain in response to an emotion or action by another person. These neurons may provide evidence for the brain processes behind bonding. Mirror neurons are activated in mothers during non-verbal imitation of their infant's facial expressions. These emotional centers of the brain are possibly engaged to a greater extent when maternal empathy is higher. This empathy is measured by how much a mother pays attention and thinks about her infant's feelings and experience.</transcript>
			<notes id="mentor-character">Narrator:</notes>
			<eventlist>
				<event type="PLAYHEAD_CHANGE" pos="1" result="SHOW" target="ref_icon01" result_param=""/>
			</eventlist>
		</audio>
		<audio id="narration03">
			<file play="false" startpos="1" bytes="73139" duration="214">a_02_03_01_010_03.swf</file>
			<transcript translate="true">Before we continue discussing what parents can do to help build attachment, let's go over the following Key Messages for this section. They are:  Every time a parent responds to a child's cue, the child builds security. Children learn through repeated experiences in ordinary moments.</transcript>
			<notes id="mentor-character">Narrator:</notes>
